tools_called.args:
{"query": "What are the effects of amending soil with different types of organic materials?", "summary": "Based on the action documents, different types of organic soil amendments show various effects on soil properties and crop performance. Compost amendments increase soil organic matter levels, microbial biomass and fruit yield (action 889). Mixed organic and inorganic amendments result in higher microbial biomass and activity, increased microbial diversity, and more effective reduction of cracks in dry soil compared to inorganic fertilizers alone (action 902). These mixed amendments also increase soil organic carbon levels and nutrients, and can increase maize yield (action 902).

Manure amendments show varied effects on soil properties. They increase organic matter content in some studies while showing similar amounts in others, with mixed results for nitrogen content, increased phosphorus and potassium levels, and varied pH effects (action 1363). Manure reduces soil erosion, increases soil stability, but leads to higher greenhouse gas emissions including carbon dioxide and nitrous oxide (action 1363). When combined with agricultural composts, manures increase microbial biomass and respiration, reduce soil loss and water runoff, increase carbon levels and organic matter, improve soil physical properties including larger soil aggregations, and increase crop yields (action 911).

Municipal waste composts greatly reduce soil loss and water runoff in semi-arid soils, though show mixed results in other contexts (action 890). In wetland environments, large amounts of compost can alter plant community composition toward drier conditions, reduce plant species richness and diversity, but increase individual plant size such as birch saplings while maintaining similar overall vegetation biomass (action 3310). Charcoal additions to soil increase legume cover but do not alter overall plant biomass or grass cover (action 3422).", "action_ids": ["889","902","1363","911","890","3310","3422"]}

